  <!-- v0.14.0 -->
  <h2 id="v0140">v0.14.0 — Five New Modules</h2>

  <h3 id="v0140-waf">AWS WAF Bridge</h3>
  <p>
    Araxys <strong>AWS WAF Bridge</strong> generates AWS WAF rules directly from your OpenAPI specifications. Instead of manually writing WAF rules and keeping them in sync with your API, the bridge reads your OpenAPI schema and produces WAF rules that match your endpoints:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Schema-driven rule generation</strong>: Parses OpenAPI 3.x specs and generates rate-based, IP-based, and SQLi/XSS inspection rules matching your actual API surface</li>
    <li><strong>boto3 apply</strong>: Directly applies generated rules to your AWS WAF Web ACL using boto3 — no manual AWS Console clicks</li>
    <li><strong>Multi-strike escalation</strong>: Configurable escalation chain that moves from COUNT→BLOCK after repeated violations within a time window</li>
    <li><strong>CLI integration</strong>: <code>araxys waf generate</code> and <code>araxys waf apply</code> commands for CI/CD pipelines</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 id="v0140-threat-intel">Threat Intelligence Feeds</h3>
  <p>
    Araxys <strong>Threat Intelligence Feeds</strong> imports, normalizes, and resolves IP reputation from 8 external threat intelligence sources. The <code>IPResolver</code> answers "should I trust this IP?" before your application processes the request:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>8 feed sources</strong>: AlienVault OTX, AbuseIPDB, Blocklist.de, Cisco Talos, Emerging Threats, FireHOL, Spamhaus DROP, and Tor Exit Nodes</li>
    <li><strong>IPResolver</strong>: Unified query interface that aggregates reputation scores across all configured feeds with configurable confidence thresholds</li>
    <li><strong>Background scheduler</strong>: Automatically refreshes feed data on configurable intervals — no cron jobs needed</li>
    <li><strong>CLI</strong>: <code>araxys threatintel lookup &lt;ip&gt;</code>, <code>araxys threatintel refresh</code>, <code>araxys threatintel feeds</code> for debugging and manual inspection</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 id="v0140-graphql">GraphQL Security</h3>
  <p>
    Araxys <strong>GraphQL Security</strong> protects your GraphQL endpoints from resource exhaustion and information disclosure attacks. It uses <code>graphql-core</code> AST analysis to enforce limits BEFORE query execution:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>4 validators</strong>: Depth limit (max query nesting), Breadth limit (max selections per level), Cost limit (weighted complexity analysis), and Introspection disable (block schema introspection in production)</li>
    <li><strong>graphql-core AST</strong>: Validates queries at the AST level — no regex hacks, no string matching</li>
    <li><strong>ASGI middleware</strong>: Integrates at the ASGI layer, blocking malicious queries before they reach your resolvers</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 id="v0140-headers-audit">Security Headers Audit</h3>
  <p>
    Araxys <strong>Security Headers Audit</strong> scans your application's HTTP response headers against 9 OWASP-recommended security checks. Use it in CI or as a sampling middleware to catch missing headers before attackers do:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>9 OWASP checks</strong>: HSTS, CSP, X-Content-Type-Options, X-Frame-Options, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy, Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy, Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy, Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy</li>
    <li><strong>Sampling middleware</strong>: Configure a sample rate (e.g., 5% of responses) to audit headers in production without performance impact</li>
    <li><strong>CLI</strong>: <code>araxys headers audit &lt;url&gt;</code> for ad-hoc and CI pipeline checks</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 id="v0140-secrets-rotation">Dynamic Secrets Rotation</h3>
  <p>
    Araxys <strong>Dynamic Secrets Rotation</strong> automatically rotates database credentials, API keys, and other secrets on a configurable schedule without downtime — using a hot-swap pattern that replaces the active secret while the old one remains valid during a transition window:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Background Task loop</strong>: Runs on configurable <code>rotation_interval</code> — generates new secrets, stores them, and triggers the hot-swap</li>
    <li><strong>Pool hot-swap</strong>: Connection pools are atomically replaced with new credentials — existing connections drain gracefully while new connections use the rotated secret</li>
    <li><strong>Admin API</strong>: <code>POST /admin/secrets/rotate</code> for on-demand rotation, <code>GET /admin/secrets/status</code> for rotation history</li>
    <li><strong>CLI</strong>: <code>araxys secrets rotate</code>, <code>araxys secrets status</code>, <code>araxys secrets audit</code></li>
  </ul>

  <h3 id="v0140-testing">Testing</h3>
  <p>
    v0.14.0 ships with <strong>1958 tests</strong>, <strong>mypy strict</strong> mode enabled across all source files, and <strong>Ruff clean</strong> — zero linter warnings. Every new module includes comprehensive unit tests, integration tests, and edge-case coverage.
  </p>

  <!-- v0.13.0 -->
  <h2 id="v0130">v0.13.0 — XXE Protection & OIDC Discovery</h2>

  <h3 id="v0130-xxe">XXE Protection</h3>
  <p>
    Araxys <strong>XXE Protection</strong> detects and blocks XML External Entity attacks — including billion-laughs entity expansion, file disclosure via SYSTEM entities, SSRF via external entities, and DTD-based attacks. The module uses a <strong>3-stage scanning strategy</strong> with <strong>zero required external dependencies</strong>:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Regex pre-scan</strong>: Catches <code>&lt;!DOCTYPE</code>, <code>&lt;!ENTITY</code>, <code>SYSTEM</code>, and <code>PUBLIC</code> patterns before any parser touches the input</li>
    <li><strong>defusedxml (optional)</strong>: When installed (<code>araxys[xxe]</code>), provides parser-level protection with automatic fallback</li>
    <li><strong>stdlib fallback</strong>: <code>xml.etree.ElementTree</code> on pre-validated XML (safe because the pre-scan already blocked dangerous declarations)</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-block-header">
      <span class="code-block-lang">python</span>
      <button class="code-block-copy">Copy</button>
    </div>
    <pre><code set:html={`<span class="token-keyword">from</span> araxys <span class="token-keyword">import</span> AraxysConfig
<span class="token-keyword">from</span> araxys.core.config <span class="token-keyword">import</span> XXEConfig

config = <span class="token-function">AraxysConfig</span>(
    <span class="token-param">secret_key</span>=<span class="token-string">"your-32-char-secret-key-here!!!!"</span>,
    <span class="token-param">xxe</span>=<span class="token-function">XXEConfig</span>(
        <span class="token-param">forbid_dtd</span>=<span class="token-bool">True</span>,
        <span class="token-param">forbid_entities</span>=<span class="token-bool">True</span>,
        <span class="token-param">forbid_external</span>=<span class="token-bool">True</span>,
    ),
)`} /></pre>
  </div>

  <h3 id="v0130-oidc">OIDC Discovery (RFC 8414)</h3>
  <p>
    Araxys <strong>OIDC Discovery</strong> client fetches, validates, and caches OpenID Connect provider metadata from the well-known endpoint. Instead of hardcoding authorization, token, and JWKS endpoints, provide just the <code>issuer_url</code> and Araxys discovers the rest automatically:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>RFC 8414 compliant</strong>: Validates <code>issuer</code>, <code>authorization_endpoint</code>, <code>token_endpoint</code>, and <code>jwks_uri</code> as required fields</li>
    <li><strong>In-memory TTL cache</strong>: Configurable cache TTL (default 5 minutes) reduces network requests</li>
    <li><strong>OIDCDiscoveryError</strong>: Raised on network, timeout, or parse failures with the <code>issuer_url</code> context</li>
    <li><strong>Zero extra deps</strong>: Uses httpx, which is already a core Araxys dependency</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-block-header">
      <span class="code-block-lang">python</span>
      <button class="code-block-copy">Copy</button>
    </div>
    <pre><code set:html={`<span class="token-keyword">from</span> araxys <span class="token-keyword">import</span> OIDCDiscoveryClient

client = <span class="token-function">OIDCDiscoveryClient</span>()
metadata = <span class="token-keyword">await</span> client.<span class="token-function">discover</span>(<span class="token-string">"https://accounts.google.com"</span>)

<span class="token-builtin">print</span>(metadata.<span class="token-param">authorization_endpoint</span>)
<span class="token-comment"># https://accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/v2/auth</span>
<span class="token-builtin">print</span>(metadata.<span class="token-param">token_endpoint</span>)
<span class="token-comment"># https://oauth2.googleapis.com/token</span>`} /></pre>
  </div>

  <!-- v0.12.0 -->
  <h2 id="v0120">v0.12.0 — Malware Scanning</h2>
  <p>
    Araxys <strong>Malware Scanner</strong> detects malicious file uploads using <strong>9 heuristic detectors</strong> — all pure Python with <strong>zero external AV dependencies</strong>. No ClamAV, no VirusTotal, no external binaries required.
  </p>

